Aug 8 2009 	Excellent service from all areas	This was our fourth trip to Dubai but our first stay at this hotel, previously we have always stayed at the JBH where we had a great time. We booked a Gold Club double room as we are now used to the 'extras' you get with these facilites having always gone Exec/Gold.We arrived at the hotel at around 0130hrs after a decent flight in from BHX with Emirates, on arrival the service was excellent considering the time, with our bags going one way and us being escourted to the Gold Club for check in. This was achieved quickley and we were in the room, with bags delivered by 0200hrs.The rooms were spotlessly clean as were the bathroom facilities, though compared to our previous experiences the rooms were somewhat smaller in comparision, we did adapt to the surroundings though so i wouldn't hold it against them.During our stay we requested that the minibar be emptied, which they did immediatley which allowed the storage of our own sensibly priced 'stuff'. (Hotel managers...price your minibar stock sensibly and people may actually consume it!) There is no iron/board in the rooms though once you request one it is delivered and stays with you for the duration. No tea/coffee making facilites though we were less than a minute from the Gold club lounge where it was available 24hrs if need be. Lots of Gilchrist and Soames toiletries, rooms serviced twice daily (inc turn down service) and the fruit bowl was also changed daily if you wanted it. ( i usually waited until i'd eaten what i had to save waste). We are quite sure also that the bed linen was changed daily, every day's a 'clean sheet' day.Whilst walking around the corridors of the hotel, ALL the staff were friendly and helpful. The hotel is currently undergoing some renovation and therefore there is some construction noise thoughout the day but it's hardly noticed at the pool area, which is where you normally are during the day.The room had a balcony with table and chairs which faced the sea though our view was obstructed by palm trees. What is nice about this hotel are the grounds, lots of grass and well kept planted areas.We made good use of the Gold club which would provide a light breakfast in the morning, we only used this once when we overslept, otherwise we tended to breakfast at Olives or more regularly Celebrations. The Gold club was used for impromptu drinks (24hrs), the afternoon tea (1500 to 1700rs) and then drinks/cocktails from 1800 to 2000hrs. The guys in the Gold club, Manoj and Tijo? worked tirelessly and once they new your tipple would provide it with a simple 'thumbs up'. They can provide cocktails of the common variety if requested, i.e. Margarita's, pina colada, manhattans etc. With the afternoon tea and canapes with drinks we were never really hungry. The service was excellent in the Club lounge which also has its own concierge and internet access on two PC's. There is also limited free wireless access in one area of the club lounge.We got half board included which permits either 'included' meals at Olive's restaurant or you get a Table de Hote menu at the beach bar and grill or Tagine. In any of the complex restaurants you can have 'A la carte' menus with a 135 AED per person allowance. This means that as long as you stay away from the lobster, you can have a very nice meal for not much extra. (If you have water at the table, unless you specify the house water, they will supply a bottle of Evian for 50 AED compared to 10AED for the normal stuff) Overall the food is excellant and the 135AED allowance covers you at ALL the Royal Mirage restaurants, booking is advisable. Celebrity's was open for breakfast only until end of August 2009.Taxis are plentiful, though they are kept about 200m from the entrance, so don't be put off if there are none in view outside of the hotel, within a minute of requesting one from concierge it will be there.What was noticable compared to our previous holidays at the JBH was that the Palace is quieter, in the JBH there is an almost constant 'buzz' on the ground floor with lots of people moving around. I would say that if you want a peace and quiet then The Palace would be the better choice.While we were there we went on a guided tour of the Arabian Court hotel to compare the facilites, the rooms were larger and the hotel design, though still Arabic, was different. The one bedroom suite we saw was superb. Point to note however, there is NO gold club in the Arabian court.All in all we had a nice time and would return to this hotel complex.	
Aug 8 2009 	Some aspects very nice and others disappointing	We recently spent a week's holiday at the Palace and were a little disappointed by the environmental effects of some of the nearby building developments. As on each of our previous visits, the hotel was very clean, all the staff were very polite and helpful and the food was good (although the buffet food was not very warm - a problem which is difficult for any kitchen to overcome).Unfortunately, due to the development of the Palm (which is adjacent to the hotel), the sea appears cloudy and we were not able to see any fish. Also, the views from the beach have (in our view) been spoilt by the erection of many high rise buildings along the coast line. The hotel does not provide complimentary internet connection and the daily charges are high. As it is possible to use the internet without charge in all nearby coffee bars, we feel it should be possible for the hotel to offer a similar service to guests. Similarly, the price of wine (and mini-bar soft drinks) is high e.g., one bottle of standard quality wine costs approx £36. The adult pool was closed during our stay and therefore it was difficult to find a quiet spot to swim during the day.	
