Nov 1 2008 	Nearly perfect!	My family and I visited in October and had an absolutely wonderful stay - despite the odd issue Im sure nobody will be disappointed staying here. We are a very fussy, well travelled family with grown up children so I will do my best to give our view.The hotel is stunning - authentic Arabic touches such as the camels at the entrance etc make you really feel like you are in Dubai - we had a look at the Westin next door and it was in contrast very corporate - you could have been anywhere in the world. So whilst some reviewers have branded the Arabic touches 'naff' I wouldn’t agree. The pool is beautiful and large, if a little crowded - the hotel was full when we were there. A lot of small children/babies were there and there was no childrens pool (Its not a particularly child friendly place considering the heat and romantic style of the hotel) so for that reason we stayed on the beach, which was lovely and much quieter. We were very apprehensive about the extent of building work going on but although its a shame about the view of the gulf being obstructed by cranes etc, there is no noise and you soon get used to it. One thing I would add is that the more pricey Palace section of the hotel is close to a new hotel construction and would possibly have some noise from this.The spa deserves a special mention - it was beautiful. Expensive but no more so that other top 5 star properties. I would advise anyone to have one of the rituals in the authentic hamman, it was incredible.Restaurants were all stunning but needed to be booked a day in advance. We were on half board and it was excellent value. The wait time for food was fairly long but I suppose thats in keeping with the romantic atmosphere. We therefore favoured the buffet restaurants which were surprisingly excellent -at Rotiserie the food was the best we have ever had on a holiday, which is some feat! If Im being pernickety I would say breakfast at Olives wasn’t the best Ive had - more selection needed.Staff were excellent - very polite and could not do enough for you.The only downside was the rooms. We felt they were quite average for a hotel of this calibre. Beautiful Arabian style bathroom and dressing area, but very small balcony and the room itself was on the small side, a little bland, and worst of all two single beds....expected two queens/doubles. Be warned there are also a few smoking rooms at the hotel and despite requesting a non smoking, guess what we ended up with! After complaining to the manager we were moved...but not what you need when you've arrived at 3am.The only other issue was that the concierge was totally incompetent. They were awful, not making restaurant reservations when asked, lacking info about golf etc. With regard to dress code some people got dressed up for dinner, some didn't...whatever you choose. We even noticed the odd football shirt at breakfast (groan) The 'cover up' rules for women do not apply to the hotel and apart from avoiding anything too short or low cut when you leave the hotel the Arabs are tolerant.We checked out the Mandinant Jumeriah and Atlantis which are 10/15 minutes away - very nice but tourist hotspots so great to visit but would have hated to have stayed somewhere so hectic. The Burj is just too OTT. So all in all I wouldn’t stay anywhere else in Dubai and hope to return soon!	
