Sep 9 2008 	The Royal Mirage is out of this world	We've just got back from a week staying at the Palace. It was the best experience we've had and its going to be hard to find a holiday to beat it. Fresh flowers &amp; fruit every day was a nice touch. The service was great, and the pool at the palace was always quiet, there was never any need to rush out and get your towels by the pool, so you can enjoy your breakfast. I would recommend using the other hotel facilities at the Arabian Court and Residence. Take a walk to the Arabian court in the morning for breakfast, great food. We were on the half board at the Palace and you could use all of the restaurants in the complex, as they have a 3 course set menu at all of the restaurants for people on the half board option or you get a credit of 125 dirhams per person from the a la carte which will normally get you a good main course. The Eau Zone at Arabian Court had great food on the half board, and superb service. I also used the fitness centre at the Spa most days which was very well equipped, and the attendents were very helpful, bringing cold towels, water etc when they saw me getting tired! The Spa is stunning. There is a smaller fitness centre at the Palace which is also great.An air conditioned car is also available to ferry you between the hotels on the complex so you don't get hot when moving around for dinner etc. The drinks at the hotel are expensive about £5 for a beer or glass of wine, so make sure you go to the duty free at the airport when you land at Dubai or Abu Dhabi, and have a drink on your balcony before you go out. The roof top bar at Arabian court was good with a happy hour from 19.30 to 20.30.We went during Ramadan which was no problem at all, probably a good thing because the hotel was fairly quiet &amp; you can get food on the complex during the day but no alcohol is served before 19.30, which really was not an issue. The shopping malls are great, but no eating in public was allowed in Ramadan, didn't stop me sneaking to the toilets for a quick drink &amp; snack. You could start eating in public at around 18.30. The Mall of the Emirates was massive, if like me you go with your girlfriend who likes shopping but you don't, go the the cinema or go skiing whilst they shop till they drop!Metered taxis are very easy to get hold of, but try not to travel into the town centre at rush hour 16.00 - 18.30, as the traffic is really terrible even tho they have 12 lane roads! A rail link is being built but will not be complete for another year.We flew into Abu Dhabi on Etihad, this was a cheaper option than Emirates into Dubai, a free bus is provided by Etihad from Abu Dhabi Airport to Dubai Bus Station, but we got a fixed price taxi for 275 Dirhams £40, direct to the hotel from Abu Dhabi airport which is a much easier option, and its about an hour journey. Much quicker than the coach &amp; less hassle.On the way back we got a meter taxi from the hotel to Abu Dhabi airport which was 180 Dirhams (£30). The service on Etihad was great with really good new movies. There was free interet access at the hotel for about 10 minutes, then you may have to pay a small amount after this time, I wasn't charged tho.The Royal Mirage is a very sophisticated &amp; refined hotel, and when we visited some of the others I found them a bit tacky, we went to the Burj Al Arab for drinks and this was very tacky inside which is a shame as it is stunning from the outside. I also found the Mina A Salaam a little fake &amp; fairy land, but this all depends on what you are looking for, as they are of course great hotels with loads of facilities. The beach at the Mirage was also massive, and the building work on the Palm is not a problem,as its not very close, its also kinda interesting to see all the development. There's always loads of sun beds available, with lots of space between them so you are not crammed in, the beach is huge.The weather in September was not too hot as you kept being given cold towels &amp; iced water. The sea was also nice and warm.Have a great time at the Palace, it really is fantastic.	
Sep 7 2008 	OK!	My partner and i stayed here in august. He was on business for 2 weeks and i joined him for a week. Being a fussy dollybird i always like the top fancy but trendy hotels, but like to find somewhere thats not as expensive or ornate as the burj al arab!The One and only was ok, I liked it and everyone was very attentive to us, but do think its lacking in 5* status. we stayed in the gold club area of hotel (which is a little bit extra-not much more than standard room price, where you got free breakfast, drinks and afternoon tea, which was very nice! and worth the extra). Being out of season august it was crazy humid/hot, but bearable. We booked direct with the hotel and were paying almost £400 per night, whereas lots of the other guests we talked to had booked 'cheap packages' through agents for almost half that, which kinda cheapens the place. Our room was standard nice, and maid service good. Restaurants were good although quite pricey.The arabian court decor was gorgeous, more modern than the palace-but their pool area was crampt and they dont have the gold club deal rooms. The pool at the palace is great, nice and big, it was hard to get loungers after mid-day although the beach was always quiet. The residence and spa seemed more exclusive, you couldnt get me out of the spa-haman. Also the hairdressers were amazing, after 3 years of visiting top mayfair salons attempting to colour my bleached blonde hair darker, the morrocan girl there did an amazing job that no other hairdresser in the world (litterally) has done! The new westin is right next door to the palace and looks very nice. Also the one and only are opening the atlantis on the palm (which we could see whilst on the beach) which looks identical to the bahamas one and will be interesting to see what its like without the american aspect!.The daily round up of guests for volley-ball in the pool was more reminisent of a cheap euro package holiday hotel, but it was nice to see all the guests making friends in the process!. We visited the madinat where you have the 3 hotels ;mina-al-salam, al qusar etc and they seemed a bit nicer but they were more busy and touristy-kinda more fake/plasticy like vegas hotels, like the wynn resort. The royal mirage has got a nice quieter position than the madinat i think. Had dinner in the asian restaurant in the burj al arab, food and service was exceptional and bill was £300 for the 2 of us, but it was a buffet style so you could eat as much as you liked!, followed with drinks in the top bar, views amazing, altho seemed everyone couldnt relax-got that impression in the burj, lots of glam russians. had the best peach bellini for £30!Taxi drivers there drive like maniacs although its peanuts to go anywhere, just wear your seatbelt. Didnt like the way of life there, example; was in the ladies toilets of a shopping mall queing, and there was a chinese girl in front of me, and a soap attendant lady standing by,- a cubicle became free and the chinese girl went to go in it, then a old arab lady in full clothing walked in and the soap attendant, stopped the chinese girl and said &quot;no this lady first&quot; and the chinese girl stood back. unbelievable. Also the workers in the mirage say they only get £150 a month for 20 hr days and the indians get treated really badly. My partners opening a branch of his business out there and various expats told him that the culture is arabs 1st, english 2nd..the rest get treated with contempt. Also if your a glamorous women (im a retired model) then your only good for one thing!.Mall of the emirates, excellent shopping. Head to Aizone if youre a wag-spent £2k in there. Went to karama, as id heard about the amazing copies you could find there. was very dissapointed, hassled minute we got out of taxi. I have many real bags and watches, but lately got some fakes from a website a friend uses. The bags and watches were all bad obvious copies. and several shops tried to sell me the same chanel j2 ceramic, one for £50, one for £200.When i told them i wanted swiss-quality copies (which are usually like £300 each) they just tried to sell me the chinese £20 copies for £300. Love the grovesnor house hotel (very minimalist and trendy, but no good as no beach) and the gary rhodes restaurant (very white like the sanderson) is top notch. Ive stayed in the royal meridien beach hotel last year (with ok mag as im a stylist) and thats much cheaper altho hideous 80's carpets and not really trendy and too far from the action. Also heard the pallazzo versace's opening there and is mega luxurious.Like dubai, must visit to see for yourself. All 3 hotels that make up one and only are very nice, although get a good deal as i think it wasnt really upto the price we paid.	
