Aug 19 2007	Wonderful despite my fears	This was very much a spontaneous break (4 days before departure date!) for our family of four and I spent hours and hours on the internet trying to find accommodation in Dubai but everything was 'on request' and we just didn't have time to provisionally book on this basis. I phoned Dubai hotels direct in desperation but all my favourite choices were fully booked. I eventually spoke to an agent who said they had guaranteed rooms at The Palace. This is why I was worried, what was wrong with this hotel that it had vacancies whereas others didn't?I was also keen to fly with Virgin Atlantic but the only option available was Air Emirates. I am so glad this was the case as they were superb, plenty of legroom, excellent food and great choice of films that you could stop and start on a whim. I even received a free Daily Mail and Hello magazine in the boarding lounge which was a treat as I am an avid reader.My fears about the Palace were totally unfounded as it was beautiful and our rooms were spacious and the bathrooms luxurious and believe me we are very critical. I don't think we were lucky enough to have the cleaner with OCD as per previous posters, unfortunately housekeeping was my only complaint. The flowers in our room on day one were looking worse for wear and were totally dead by the time we left 5 days later. The room was only given a basic tidy and our possessions were left untouched. Also, they came so late in the day that if you retired to your room at 4pm to escape the heat, they were often still in there.Olives was lovely for breakfast, lunch and dinner. We ate at Nina one evening but I did not think it was that special. The Beach Bar aand Grill was excellent and furthermore had the half board menu. We too had a free upgrade to half board. In our limited time there we visited the Gold Souk, Madinat Jumeirah Souk (my 1st choice of hotel if it had been available) and the Emirates Mall. Our best trip was the Sundowner where you venture across desert dunes in a 4x4, stop at a camel farm, stop for a sunset photo opportunity and then arrive at &quot;camp&quot; where you can have a brief camel ride and then you are served with a BBQ, plenty of drink and watch a bellydancing show. It was expensive but worth it.My only disappointment was Wild Wadi Water Park which is overrated and overpriced. If you have visited a Disney Water Park then you would understand why. It cost over £150 for the 4 of us, the main family ride was closed and there really was not an awful lot to do there. We struggled to fill half a day.We were warned about how hot it would be over there but you really have no concept until you arrive. On day 1 we walked from one end of our resort to the other and my 13 year old daughter passed out cold and then came round vomiting. This can be avoided though as there is a complimentary air conditioned shuttle to transport you around the resort. The evening we ventured into the desert, it was 50 degrees at 7pm. The locals were telling uus late September to March is the best time to go.We did not venture to the most upmarket section The Residence as I was worried I would feel it was nicer than the Palace and that we should have stayed there. The Arabian Court section is very nice as it is newer than the Palace and I would probably book in there if we return.Everyone raves about the Jumeirah Beach but the Palace is located in a much quieter area of the main 'New Dubai' strip so we would stay loyal to the Royal Mirage.As mentioned by a previous poster they are very keen to offer you Evian Water at dinner in copious amounts which is all very well until you discover it is about £4-5 per bottle. My husband usually doesn't worry about such things but even he was requesting local water by the last day.I was particularly worried about what to wear over there as you are warned to cover up but I saw tourists in downtown Dubai with strappy tops and shorts and there was no problem. The hotel had a post 6pm dress code requesting long trousers and shirts for the men but many visitors ignored this and were not ejected from the restaurants!Please don't hesitate to go here, the staff are wonderful particularly the concierge. Our 5 day stay was long enough to take in the local main attractions but was not long enough to enjoy all the facilities the hotel had to offer so stay longer if you can.	
Aug 12 2007 	The best we've stayed at by far	Back this week, and already planning our 7th trip out there for next year!We took out the Emirates EK38 from Birmingham/with an EK37 return. Both faultless, and having taken this flight pattern a few times, I can thoroughly recommend it.10 days booked at The Palace at the One and Only Royal Mirage were waiting…From the moment you enter with your gong arrival, you have the feeling this place is special. We were shown promptly to our room at 9am, which was a bonus, as check in was later in the day. We had a ground floor room which was great for access to the pool through the patio doors. Ask for the keys.The resort was not busy at all. There was much more greenery here than the other hotels I’ve been to, well designed and has that authentic Dubai feel. We had a free half board upgrade, which either allowed a la carte dining or 120AED per person credit on the house menu. ALL the restaurants were excellent, and we tried The Beach Bar Grill, Tangines and Olives at the Palace and Ninas, The Rotisserie and Eau Zone at the Arabian Court. Breakfast was at Olives, but it’s worth knowing they can do a room delivery service until 12 with a 45 AED surcharge (per room).The pool was BIG, and is spread over a large area, encompassing large shaded areas, with numerous palms. The kids loved it, staff were so friendly, and the cleaner had a serious case of OCD, even rearranging my wife’s make up pots in ascending order. (A previous poster must have had the same cleaner!) The ongoing work at the Palm does not affect your time here. It’s worth taking a speed boat ride (Half Hour 275AED) in to the Marina. The kids club was fine, and Fatima came seeking my 2 children at breakfast on the 1st day. Local malls: Ibn Battuta 15 AED ride and The Mall of the Emirates was 20 AED away. Presently its quicker access to the Ibn Battuta, but a useful tip is if you go to the Mall of the Emirates ask the taxi driver to drop you off at the Kempinski entrance and get in via the secondary entrance. There’s a lot of congestion, and taxi queues for dropping off are quite long due to some road works. The Toll near the Mall of the Emirates kicked in last month which can add 4 dirhams to your journey along Sheikh Zayed Road. Bur Dubai: Meena Bazaar/Al Karama (50 AED) is a good half hour away, as usual avoid rush hour times.Overall, by far the best hotel we’ve stayed at. Visited the Burj…a bit too OTT for my liking	
Jul 31 2007 	Fantastic	I wanted to take my wife away as a surprise for her 40th birthday and a work friend suggested Dubai and Airline network.com. Made contact with the rep at airline network who gave great advice and recommended Palace at the One and Only Royal Mirage.Having booked, then checked the TripAdvisor site, really smart, I know! Got a slight fright when I read some of the reviews but all I can say is having booked for five days we stayed seven.This is the best hotel I've stayed in, and I've been in a few. The staff are extremely attentive and I'm almost sure the young man who made up the room twice a day had the worse case of Obsessive compulsive disorder I've ever come across!! He even put the toiletries in descending order of height.Good pool, great food, superb facilities, fabulous weather, yes it's hot but not unbearably so.I agree with the comments on alcohol, beer is about £4 but the average bottle of wine in the hotel restaurant is between £20-£30, buy it in the duty free when you arrive.A taxi from the airport to the hotel is about £12, cheaper than a transfer booked by your agent.The break was so good that my brownie points account is almost back in the black!! The plans are currently being made for next years trip.If your travelling from N.Ireland check the direct Aer Lingus flights it should save you some money, cheapest 169 euros single!	
Jul 29 2007 	Good value and location	Stayed at this property for 2 weeks on business trip. For comfort and business environment this property is highly recommended. Nice pool which is cooled down as the temps were around 120 degrees Farenheit. Hotel has high speed internet. They wanted $1/minute. I told them I was checking out ( ;-) ) and renegotiated the rate to about $30 U.S./night. Dining is good. Take the buffet but we ate out most of time. This is my 4th trip to the region. Stayed at the Renaissance, Deira 2X which has excellent value for the buck and Grosvenor House which is comfortable but glitsy and in my opinion over rated. The Royal Mirage is convenient and the staff is highly attentive to guests needs and requirements. Overall I recommend this hotel. The sister property, Residence next door is a bit quieter with understated elegance. Staying there next trip. Bring cool clothes during summer months as it is hot.	
Jul 25 2007	Very Special Royal Mirage	Last year we stayed at the Jumeirah Beach at the same time, and whilst we had a great time there, we definitely preferred our stay at the Royal Mirage, we were in the Palace but regularly used the facilities and restaurants of the Arabian court too.We prefered the pool at the Palace. Despite there not being a huge presence of Germans you still have to get up early to secure the poolside loungers. Other reviews have sung all the hotels praises with which I wholeheartedly concur. We also particularly enjoyed the breakfasts at the hotel, there was none of the normal buffet scrum for food, waiters were happy to bring a virgin mary to your table mixed already for you and it was a spacious and relaxed affair.Sailing was not cheap at £20.00 an hour for a hobie cat. Due to the construction of the Palm opposite, which you cannot hear but can actually clearly see, and the Marina to the left, the water is much calmer than at the Jumeirah Beach, no waves as such. So you have a natural large safe harbour area in which to sail.In room broadband was around £15.00 a day, whereas other local hotels charge around half that. The room connection is apparently very slow too. Luckily the business centre allows you 5 free minutes whenever you like, but after they know you will let that extend to accomodate you. Their broadband connection is mucher quiker too.You never run out of towels in your room or water, the gyms are small but well equipped and the gym staff very eager to offer advice, stretch you out after a run or workout and ply you with cold free water and fruit.All restaurant and bar bills already have tax and service included and you do not feel pressured or beholden to tip on top. We did however leave a tip for our room attendant.Taxis are very frequent and easy to come by, and it is definitely worth paying the two Salik charges, which saves an awful lot of time from the airport and only increases the bill by just over a pound.I made one journey to the airport in less than 20 minutes.There is a 7/11 store but its a very humid 10 minute walk away.Buy your alcohol at the Airport Duty Free on arrival which is very cheap because drinking profusely at the Hotel will cost you bigtime. The Thai coconut milk soup at the Ozone was both spicy sublime.Lastly in the restaurants they push water on you at £4.00 a bottle.. ask them for the local water its half the price and its what you have been drinking for free in your room and around the pool, and be aware they tend to try to top you up with new bottles which you may not have asked for.Would definitely stay there again.	
