Aug 23 2005	one and only worst hotel experience	Following is the complaint letter submitted to hotel manager following our stay:I am writing to inform you about my complete dissatisfaction with a recent stay at one of your company’s properties. Having been enamored by the promise of a one and only experience at one of your properties, I booked a twin room at the Royal Mirage (the Palace) Dubai from June 30- July 2, 2005. With quite a wide choice of hotels available on Jumeira Beach, I chose the Royal Mirage because I thought it would be relatively less quiet than some of the hotels in the area that are marketed to families. I made my booking directly with the hotel, and the reservations agent was quite helpful in answering questions. I emphasized that I would require a twin room with two beds. I then requested a confirmation email from the agent with the details of the booking. She told me that I would receive it immediately. Assuming that that meant immediately, I expected it immediately. Unfortunately, it was not to be. I called back the next day, requesting the email once again. The agent asked if I have a fax number so she could fax the document. I called back the next day, requesting the email once again. The agent asked if I have a fax number so she could fax the document. I replied that I do not have access to a fax machine and would therefore prefer email. I waited, but the confirmation email did not arrive. I called the next day (two days after the initial booking was made) to request yet again for the confirmation email to be sent to me. The email finally arrived that evening. The email requested that a signed copy of the form be returned via fax to the hotel. I faxed the document from a public fax machine, and also scanned the signed form and sent it via email to the hotel, specifically asking them to reply to me by email as I did not have a personal fax machine. That night, a confirmation was sent to the same fax machine I had used to send the form (which, as I explained above, I had explicitly requested not be used for replying). It was only by pure coincidence that I received the confirmation fax. I then emailed the hotel explaining what had happened and asking yet again not to use the fax for any correspondence. I got an email back, confirming that only email will be used from then on, with no apology for the inconvenience this had caused me.Upon arrival at the airport, I made my way to the hotel counter for my pre-booked airport transfer. It took around 5 minutes while the agent was on the phone not informing us of how long it would take. He then led us outside, where we again waited at least 5 minutes in the sticky summer heat for the car to pull up to greet us. While in the car, we asked the driver for some water. He told us it would be in the hand rest. We opened the hand rest; no water. He apologized and said it was finished. He did not offer to stop somewhere and get water on the way. After an otherwise comfortable ride, we arrived at the hotel where the greeting and check-in service was fantastic. The agent provided full information on restaurant location, timings, etc. We double-checked with her that the room was a twin room, and she said yes. The luggage attendance then escorted us to our room (#521), and as we walked in, we saw that there was a king-size bed against a head-board. We informed him that there must be a mistake as we had asked for two beds. He told us that these were two separate beds and that he could separate them for us if we so wished. He then proceeded to basically rearrange our room while we waited, separating the beds and placing the bedside cabinet between them. This resulted in one bed being against an oversized king headboard, and the other bed being in the corner without. This seems quite a strange arrangement for what would normally be expected from a twin room, and was unacceptable given that the request had been made clear from the time of reservation. In any case, we accepted the ‘while-you-wait’ reconfiguration and tipped the attendant for his efforts.As we unpacked our belongings, we realized that once again, there was no bottled water in the room, which is the norm in Dubai hotels. We called Room Service and requested a large bottle of mineral water. They informed us that the hotel provides complementary water and that they would send some right up. That process took 20 minutes, for four bottles of water. It was evident that this room had not been adequately prepared in time for our arrival, and as per our requirements. The next day, we skipped breakfast but thought we would go down to the lounge for some coffee. There were around three tables occupied so we assumed there was service. We sat at a table and waited. And waited. There was one waitress behind the counter who did not acknowledge our presence, ten minutes later. We got frustrated with the lack of service and decided to go to the Arabian Court’s lounge. We figured, “It can’t be worse than this”. As you can probably guess, we were wrong. We sat at a table and waited. No waiters in sight. We heard clanging nearby so I went to look for someone and ended up in the kitchen asking for service. We were served, and then the waiter disappeared again. All in all, the process of having a quick cup of tea took over an hour. That evening, after a long afternoon of shopping, we decided to relax at the Residence and Spa. We called the concierge to see if they would still be serving Afternoon Tea at the Library, and he informed us that they would. So we got dressed and went down to take the shuttle. At the same time we called Housekeeping to request that they clean the bathroom and change the towels while we were gone. As we were heading out, the gentleman at the concierge came over to us and said that actually they were no longer serving tea, but that the lounge would still be open for drinks. We headed over anyway to explore the property.We made our way to the Library and seated ourselves. The waiter came over and asked us what we would like to have. We looked on the table for a menu; no menu. We had to ask for one. This was truly the one and only hotel I had ever been in at which you are not given a menu before you are asked for your order. Once we went back to the room, we discovered that the bathroom had not been cleaned as we had requested; however, some additional toiletries had been brought up. We had to call Housekeeping again to repeat our request that the bathroom be cleaned. In any case, thank goodness we were leaving the next day. We were going out for lunch and had requested a late check-out. On our way out, I asked the Reception to send a copy of the bill up to the room so we could review it quickly prior to check-out. She proceeded to print it out and promised that she would send it up immediately. Two hours later, we returned to the hotel to pack and check-out. We looked for the bill in the room; nothing. We called the Reception and informed them that their colleague had promised to send it up. We were told that they would send someone up immediately. Fifteen minutes later, there was a knock on the door. I opened the door to see a luggage attendant with a trolley. I informed him that we had requested a copy of the bill, not a trolley, and that we would call down when our luggage was ready for collection. Ten minutes later, we got the bill. This was a delay of at least three hours from the time we had requested it. So, a weekend which we had expected to be a one- of- a- kind experience turned out to be truly that; expect that the experience was miserable. The level of service, quality of the room, and ability to meet expectations were all extremely disappointing. While we, as regular tourists to Dubai, have a wide range of hotels to choose from, it is a shame for the hotel that claims to be the ‘One and Only’ to have such a wonderful physical facility but not be able to deliver on any promises in order to encourage me to be a repeat guest.I would strongly request that you take into serious consideration the events detailed above and take remedial action. A beautiful physical building with a great landscape is of little use if it is built on such a poor foundation.	
